Suppose $f(x)=\frac{3}{2-x}$. If $g(x)=\frac{1}{f^{-1}(x)}+9$, find $g(3)$.
inference:
Solution:
First, we must find the inverse of $f(x)$. To do this, we switch $x$ and $y$ and solve for $y$:
$$x = \frac{3}{2-y}$$
$$x(2-y) = 3$$
$$2x - xy = 3$$
$$-xy = 3 - 2x$$
$$y = \frac{3 - 2x}{-x}$$
$$y = \frac{2x - 3}{x}$$
Therefore, $f^{-1}(x) = \frac{2x - 3}{x}$.

Now, we can plug this into our expression for $g(x)$:
$$g(x) = \frac{1}{\frac{2x-3}{x}} + 9$$
$$g(x) = \frac{x}{2x-3} + 9$$
$$g(x) = \frac{x + 9(2x-3)}{2x-3}$$
$$g(x) = \frac{x + 18x - 27}{2x-3}$$
$$g(x) = \frac{19x - 27}{2x-3}$$

Finally, we can find $g(3)$:
$$g(3) = \frac{19(3) - 27}{2(3) - 3}$$
$$g(3) = \frac{57 - 27}{6 - 3}$$
$$g(3) = \frac{30}{3}$$
$$g(3) = 10$$

Final Answer: $\boxed{10}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: Substituting $f^{-1}(x)$ into our expression for $f$, we get \[\frac{3}{2-f^{-1}(x)}=x.\]Solving for $f^{-1}(x)$, we find that $f^{-1}(x)=2-\frac{3}{x}$, so $f^{-1}(3)=2-\frac{3}{3}=1$. Therefore, $g(3)=\frac{1}{f^{-1}(3)}+9=\frac{1}{1}+9=\boxed{10}$.
